 **Problem description:**
Adding a ValidationRule in code behind (because it rely on a value which is not known on startup) does not update validation the intuition way. Try to get arround this and call `ValidationWithoutUpdate` does nothing.
 
 **Actual behavior:** <!-- callstack for crashes / exceptions -->
You have to call UpdateSource() before ValidateWithoutUpdate()
 **Expected behavior:**
 ValidateWithoutUpdate() would update validation without require of UpdateSource()
 **Minimal repro:**

```
    public partial class MainWindow : Window
    {
        public class NameRule : ValidationRule
        {
            public int AdditionalInformationWhichWouldRequireBinding { get; set; }
            public override ValidationResult Validate(object value, CultureInfo cultureInfo)
            {
                int age = 0;
                try
                {
                    if (((string)value).Length > 0)
                        age = int.Parse((String)value);
                }
                catch (Exception e)
                {
                    return new ValidationResult(false, $"Illegal characters or {e.Message}");
                }

                if(AdditionalInformationWhichWouldRequireBinding < age)
                    return new ValidationResult(false, $"Illegal Range");

                return ValidationResult.ValidResult;
            }
        }

        NameRule _nameRule;

        public MainWindow()
        {
            InitializeComponent();

            var binding = BindingOperations.GetBinding(txtNewName, TextBox.TextProperty);
            var bindingex = BindingOperations.GetBindingExpression(txtNewName, TextBox.TextProperty);
            var role = new NameRule();
            binding.ValidationRules.Add(role);
            _nameRule = role;
            DataContextChanged += MainWindow_DataContextChanged;
            DataContext = new NewViewModel
            {
                NewName = "abc"
            };
        }

        private void MainWindow_DataContextChanged(object sender, DependencyPropertyChangedEventArgs e)
        {
            _nameRule.AdditionalInformationWhichWouldRequireBinding = ((NewViewModel)DataContext).RequiredForValidation;
            var binding = BindingOperations.GetBindingExpression(txtNewName, TextBox.TextProperty);

            binding.UpdateSource();
            binding.ValidateWithoutUpdate();
        }
    }

    class NewViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
    {
        private string newName;

        public string NewName { get => newName;
            set {
                newName = value;
                PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new PropertyChangedEventArgs(nameof(NewName)));
            }
        }

        public int RequiredForValidation { get; set; }

        public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;
    }
}
```

XAML:
```
<TextBox x:Name="txtNewName" Text="{Binding NewName}"/>
```

Additional:
- The first value which is validated in above example is `string.Empty` not `"abc"`.
- if ValidationResult.ValidResult is returned `ValidateWithoutUpdate` throws NullReferenceException
```
   at System.Windows.Data.BindingExpression.ConvertProposedValue(Object value)
   at System.Windows.Data.BindingExpression.ValidateAndConvertProposedValue(Collection`1& values)
   at System.Windows.Data.BindingExpressionBase.ValidateWithoutUpdate()
   at WpfNet6Test.MainWindow.MainWindow_DataContextChanged(Object sender, DependencyPropertyChangedEventArgs e)
```
- Solution would be to wait until Expression is activated and delay force valdiation with:
```
Dispatcher.BeginInvoke(DispatcherPriority.Normal, new Action(ForceValidation));

        private void ForceValidation()
        {
            var binding = BindingOperations.GetBindingExpression(txtNewName, TextBox.TextProperty);
            binding.UpdateSource();
        }
```
but `ValidateWithoutUpdate` is still without function.
